    <div class="w3-container">
    <p>In learning Ruby on Rails, I decided to take on the challenge of building a blog, using the popular Ruby on Rails tutorial as my guide. 
        This experience allowed me to explore the powerful features of Rails and understand its conventions, which significantly streamline the development process.</p>
    <p>My first step was to set up the Ruby on Rails development environment. I installed Ruby, Rails, and SQLite, which would serve as the database for my application.
        RailsInstaller was my choice on Windows, which packaged everything I needed in one place. I chose VSCode as my code editor because of its robust features and strong support for Ruby on Rails.</p>
    <p>With my environment ready, I initiated a new Rails project by running <code>rails new blog</code> in the command line. 
        This command magically set up the complete structure of my new blog application, including all directories and configuration files essential for a Rails project.</p>
    <p>Next, I generated a controller named <code>Posts</code> to manage the blog posts. This was accomplished with the command <code>rails generate controller Posts</code>. 
        Rails automatically created not only the controller file but also views associated with each action I might need, such as displaying a list of posts or a single post.</p>
    <p>For the blog to function, I needed a way to store and retrieve blog posts. This required setting up a model, which I called <code>Post</code>. 
        Using the command <code>rails generate model Post title:string body:text</code>, 
        Rails created a model along with a migration file to set up the database table. I ran <code>rails db:migrate</code> to apply this migration, 
        which created the <code>posts</code> table in my SQLite database.</p>
    <p>Implementing CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) functionality was a core part of the tutorial. I defined routes in the <code>config/routes.rb</code> file, 
        and implemented actions in the <code>Posts</code> controller to handle each operation. The Rails form helpers made it straightforward to create forms for new and edited posts, 
        leveraging Rails' convention over configuration principle.</p>
    <p>Rails' asset pipeline facilitated the addition of custom stylesheets. I added some basic CSS to enhance the layout and appearance of my blog, making it more visually appealing.</p>
    <p>Building this blog with Ruby on Rails was an enlightening experience that deepened my understanding of web development frameworks. 
        The conventions used by Rails, such as convention over configuration and the RESTful architecture of web applications, helped me develop a functional blog with minimal hassle. 
        The ability to see immediate results as I learned was incredibly satisfying, and it has spurred me to dive deeper into more advanced features of Rails.</p>
    
